1.	HTML
Hyper text markup language
Text—content
Hyper text – A text containing Multiple links(hyper links)
Markup Language- specific set of tags by using these we can create content on the websites

		Can create structured content on the website.
2.	CSS
Cascading Style Sheets
It is used to make the website in attractive and animative way
It is used to add styles to the website
Font
Color
Position
Shape
3.	JavaScript
It is used to create Dynamic Websites;
--forms validations

1.Static Websites:
HTML,CSS
--remains constant to every one
Ex: Facebook Login Page


2. Dynamic Websites
--changes to every one(data)
Ex: facebook(feed) #data


JavaScript:
Variables
1.	Static typed 
2.	Dynamically typed
Variables are used to store the data (any kind of data).
1)	Case Sensitive
2)	Start with letters, _(underscore), $(dollarsign)
3)	Cant start with numbers
4)	Reserved words(keywords) are not allowed
5)	Allow letters, _(underscore), $(dollarsign) and numbers

How to declare variables:
•	var
•	let
•	const





var name='Nani'
        console.log(name)
        document.write(name)
        var a3='Raju'
        console.log(a3)
        document.write(a3)
        var a='Venkat'
        a= 'Naveen'
        console.log(a)
        document.write(a)

Reassigning the variables is possible by var
Reassigning the variables with let  is also accepted
Reassigning with const not accepted
Uncaught TypeError: Assignment to constant variable.


var a=1
        a=5
        console.log(a+a)

        let b=1
        b=5
        b=b+b
        console.log(b)

        const c=10
        c=15
        console.log(c)




Redeclaring with var is accepted
Redeclaring with let is not accepted
	Uncaught SyntaxError: Identifier 'a' has already been declared
Redeclaring with const is not accepted
	Uncaught SyntaxError: Identifier 'a' has already been declared

 var a=10
        var a=15
        console.log(a)

        let a=1
        let a=5
        console.log(a)

        const a=3.14
        const a=120
        console.log(a)


Block Scope

Variables declared with var doesnot have block scope
Variables declared with let have block scope 

let a=11
        {
            let a=5
            console.log(a+a)
        }

        console.log(a+a)

        var b=1;
        var b=3;
        {
            var b=5;
            console.log(b+b); //10
        }
        console.log(b+b) //10


